Introduction to R and terminal environments, using these environments to analyze sanger data and leverage fastngsadmix on WGS data

Overview

In this tutorial we will go over some basics in R, process Sanger data and learn how to use FastNGSadmix to identify Ae. aegypti aegpyti and Ae. aegypti formosus on low coverage WGS. You can find the folder with all the necessary info here INSERT HERE, go ahead and download that folder

Outline

  • Terminal environment explained
  • Installing packages
  • Rstudio environment explained
  • Working with Sanger data in Rstudio
  • Installing packages
  • fastNGSadmix

Day 1: Terminal Introduction

If you are using a Mac you can open your terminal by searching “terminal”, if you are using windows then download MSYS2 https://www.msys2.org/. Your terminal will look something like this:

We will go over some basic commands in your terminal. First lets the “pwd” command to figure out where we are.

pwd

The “pwd” command prints your current directory. We can also view all the folders and files in your directory by doing:

ls -lh

Notice folders have a “/” after their name (.e.g. “Desktop/”) We can move between directories using the command “cd”. Choose some folder and move into it!

cd yourfoldername/

You can use absolute paths (the entire directory name) or relative paths to move between folders. The relative path requires you to know where a folder is relative to your current position (we just did an example of a relative path). Here’s another example of using a relative path to move around. If you want to move one directory up just do

cd ..

If you want to use an absolute path try adding the directory that was printed when you ran “pwd” previously

cd /your/entire/path/here

If you know where you saved the Princeton2024WS folder go ahead and cd to that location. If you dont know where it is you can use the “find” function.

find / -type d -name "Princeton2024WS"

Once you find the folder go ahead and unzip it

unzip Princeton2024WS*

At any point if you get some permissions error you can try using the command “sudo”. This gives you admin privileges and will prompt you for your password.

brew install findutils

Then replace the find command with gfind

Depending on your default syntax you might get an error running the above code, if so you can try the following

Day 1: Introduction to the R environment

What’s the difference between Rstudio and R?

Rstudio is a GUI (graphical user interface) tool that runs the programming language R.

Familiarize yourselves with the four panes in Rstudio. Top left is where we write our scripts, it is a text editor. Bottom left is the console- where the code gets sent from the text editor (this is the R platform) and where our outputs appear. Top right panel contains the global environment where we can see all our variables Bottom right panel is a viewer pane where we see things like plots and function explanations.

**Commenting and running code*

click run or ctrl+enter to run a line or section of code Putting a “#” before a line will result in the code not running (Shortcut is highlight line of code, or put your cursor on a line of code and type ctrl+enter) I recommend annotating every time you do something new, explaining what the code does. I also recommend copying outputs of tests that appear in the console window and pasting them in your R script so it is saved. for example

2+2+2
## [1] 6

You can assign an output to a variable, for example

answer=2+2+2
answer
## [1] 6

Notice that a variable called “answer” has now appeared in your global environment. You can click that variable to view it.

Its not just numbers/equations, you can assign anything for a variable for example

name="James Fifer"
famous_names=c("Barrack Obama","Mahatma Gandhi", "James Fifer")

^Note I used an underscore here instead of a space in famous_names. In coding languages, spaces are your enemy and underscores are your friend. Try running the code above with a space instead of an underscore and see what happens.

Functions

Functions in R are run with the function name followed by parentheses, e.g.

sum()
## [1] 0
sum(2,2)
## [1] 4

If you want to learn more about a function you can type

?sum()

Here is an overview of the main elements of the Sangerseq object:

primarySeqID – Identification of the primary sequence

primarySeq – The most likely sequence based on the florescence pattern

secondarySeqID – Secondary sequence ID. Secondary calls may not be present, but can occur when there is a signal for more than one base pair

secondarySeq – The secondary sequence

traceMatrix – A matrix containing the normalized signals for A,C,G,T.

peakPosMatrix – A matrix containing the position of the maximum peak values for each base.

peakAmpMatrix A matrix containing the maximum peak amplitudes for each base.

We can view the chromatogram, showing either primary calls only or both primary and secondary calls

chromatogram(Inversionseq, width = 250, height = 2, showcalls = "primary")

chromatogram(Inversionseq, width = 250, height = 2, showcalls = "both")

We can visualize both primary and secondary calls. When heterozygous regions of the sequence are present, the makeBaseCalls can be used to determine whether a particular peak is homozygous or heterozygous and call the appropriate bases.

The makeBaseCalls function essentially divides the sequence into a series of basecall windows and identifies the tallest peak for each fluorescence channel within the window. These peaks are converted to signal ratio to the tallest peak. A cutoff ratio (i.e. the “ratio=” parameter below) is then applied to determine if a peak is signal or noise. Peaks below this ratio are ignored. Remaining peaks in each window are used to make primary and secondary basecalls.

hetcalls = makeBaseCalls(Inversionseq, ratio = 0.5)

It is also possible to trim our data, here I give an example of trimming just the primary sequence, but you can apply the same logic to trim secondary calls as well.

First lets visualize what our sequences look like with some 5’ and 3’ trimming

chromatogram(Inversionseq, trim5 = 10, trim3 = 15)

Once we have located the region we want to trim, we can alter our primary sequence using the following code. Define the number of bases to trim

trim5 = 10
trim3 = 15

Pull out the primary sequence and trim

primarySeq = primarySeq(Inversionseq)
trimStart = trim5 + 1
trimEnd = nchar(primarySeq) - trim3
trimmedSeq = substr(primarySeq, trimStart, trimEnd)
Inversionseq_trimmed = new("sangerseq", primarySeq = trimmedSeq)

Day 1: Analysis

Using NCBI’s remote BLAST

You can also blast your data to NCBI’s database. Here I provide example of searching the nr database. Lets work with our original Inversion sequence

fasta_seq = DNAStringSet(hetcalls@primarySeq, use.names = TRUE)

Assign a name to the sequence, here we call it “hetcalls_primarySeq”

names(fasta_seq) = "hetcalls_primarySeq"

Write the sequence to a FASTA file

writeXStringSet(fasta_seq, filepath = "test.fasta")

BLAST

Execute the following in your terminal, NOT R/Rstudio

First locate where you installed your BLAST executables. Lets say they are located in “/c/Program Files/NCBI/blast-2.10.0+/bin” If you have no idea where you installed it you can run the following in your terminal

find / -name "blastx"

Once you have found the executable you have two options.

Option 1 This is the simplest option. In order to run blast type the following in your terminal

/c/Program Files/NCBI/blast-2.10.0+/bin/blastx

(if you are running windows you will have to specify blast.exe):

/c/Program Files/NCBI/blast-2.10.0+/bin/blastx.exe

Option 2 Add the executable to your PATH, this will allow you to use BLAST anywhere on your computer, but it can be a bit more difficult to setup.

nano ~/.bash_profile

Add the Directory to PATH: Add the following line to the file: export PATH=$PATH:“/c/Program Files/NCBI/blast-2.10.0+/bin” Save and Close: Save the file and close the editor (Ctrl + O to save, Ctrl + X to exit in nano). Reload the Profile: Reload the profile to apply changes:

source ~/.bashrc

Once we’ve set up the executable we can go ahead and run blast

blastx -query input.fasta -db nr -remote -out results.txt

Results will look something like this

Aligning reads

Going back to Rstudio for this section

Lets say you have sanger data for multiple samples and you want to align the reads. We can first leverage many of the same functions that we previously did with our Inversion sequence. But first, lets view all samples with the extension “.ab1”

ab1.files = list.files(pattern = "\\.ab1$", full.names = TRUE)

We can easily select just the Forward reads using the grep() function which which allows you to extract matches to some string (in this case “Forward”)

forward_reads = grep("Forward", ab1.files, value = TRUE)

Now to create an empty list, iterate through the reads and fill the list with the sequences.

sequences = list()
for (seq in (1:length(forward_reads))){
  print(forward_reads[seq])
  input=sangerseqR::read.abif(forward_reads[seq])
  inputseq = sangerseq(input)
  called=makeBaseCalls(inputseq, ratio = 0.5)
  primarycall=called@primarySeq
  sequences[[seq]]=primarycall
  names(sequences)[seq] =forward_reads[seq]
}

## [1] "./KF_004_NGY7-Q-InvE_InvE-Forward_E11.ab1"

stringsetseqs=DNAStringSet(sequences)

Day 2: FastNGSADMIX

FastNGSADMIX is a tool to quickly and reliably estimate admixture proportions and perform PCA from next generation sequencing data of a single individual. The analyses are based on genotype likelihoods of the input sample and a set of predefined reference populations. This method is particularly useful because of its high accuracy and speed, even at low sequencing depth and corrects for the biases introduced by small reference populations. You can find more information about the program here.

We can use a marker set of loci developed from Rose 2020 that can estimate genetic ancestry belonging to Aedes aegypti aegypti, Eastern Ae. aegypti formosus and Western Ae. aegypti formosus.

Admixture plot of Aedes aegypti showing three different genetic ancestries corresponding to Aedes aegypti aegypti and two lineages of Aedes aegypti formosus (East and West)

In order to run fastngsadmix, we need to go back to using our terminal. We will use angsd to estimate genotype likelihoods and then run fastngsadmix on the informative genetic loci to get estimates of genetic ancestry. We do this for each sample.

Before we run the code lets take a look at the files we have. You can do:

head filenamehere

to see the first few rows of each file.

fastngsadmix files

  • rose2020panel.3.chrom.sites- A file with chromosome and base pair position as well as information on the major and minor alleles. This allows us to tell angsd to create genotypic information for only the sites that we actually care about (in other words saves time).
  • fastadmixtest- A file that contains the filenames for every “.bam” files (.bam files are our alignment files that we get after mapping sequencing data to a reference)
  • rose2020panel.3.chrom.txt- Our panel file that include locus information, reference and alternative alleles as well as a measure of the prevalence of the reference allele in each of the three ancestral populations (aegypti aegpyti, eastern formosus or western formosus).
  • rose2020panel.3.nind.txt- These are the number of individuals that were initially used to generate info for each of the ancestral populations.

Ok now we can run the following code (should take between 30 mins and an hour)

>runfastmix
while read i; do     
CURR=$(basename "$i" .bam);     
echo -e "/path/to/program/angsd -i $i -GL 2 -sites rose2020panel.3.chrom.sites -doGlf 2 -doMajorMinor 3 -minMapQ 10 -minQ 20 -doDepth 1 -doCounts 1 -P 2 -out $CURR && /path/to/program/fastNGSadmix -likes ${CURR}.beagle.gz -fname rose2020panel.3.chrom.txt -Nname rose2020panel.3.nind.txt -out $CURR -whichPops all &"; done < fastadmixtest> runfastmix
echo "wait" >> runfastmix

This generates .qopt files for each sample. We can combine these files into one using the following code:

input="fastadmixtest"
output="fastadmixtest.qopt"

ls *.qopt | head -n 1 | xargs head -n 1 > "${output}.header.tmp"
# Step 2: Create a temporary file for concatenated data
> "${output}.data.tmp"
# Step 3: Read each line from the input file and append the content of the corresponding .qopt file (excluding the first line) to the temporary data file
while read -r line; do
    tail -n +2 "${line%.bam}.qopt" >> "${output}.data.tmp"
done < "$input"
# Step 4: Combine the header with the concatenated data
cat "${output}.header.tmp" "${output}.data.tmp" > "${output}.final.tmp"
# Step 5: Create a file with the word "adapter"
echo "adapter" > "${output}.otherheader.tmp"
# Step 6: Add "adapter" to the beginning of the input file and save it as a temporary adapter file
cat "${output}.otherheader.tmp" "$input" > "${output}.adapter.tmp"
# Step 7: Combine the header with the concatenated data and save it to the final output file
paste "${output}.adapter.tmp" "${output}.final.tmp" > "$output"

Once we have this fastadmixtest.qopt file we can go back in R and summarize the data

Day 2: Creating a map in R

There are lots of ways to make maps in R, I’ve found just using the base R plot functions and then building custom functions is the easiest for me. First lets download some more packages

library(raster)
library(geodata)
library(plotrix)
library(dplyr)

Then we will take the admixture means for each population

obs_data = merged_df %>%
  group_by(POP) %>%
  summarize(
    Latitude = mean(Latitude, na.rm = F),
    Longitude = mean(Longitude, na.rm = F),
    Aaa = mean(Aaa, na.rm = F),
    AafE = mean(AafE, na.rm = F),
    AafW = mean(AafW, na.rm = F)  
  )

Assign minimum and maximum values for the map based on geographic coordinates for the samples

max_lat = ceiling(max(obs_data$Latitude))
min_lat = floor(min(obs_data$Latitude))
max_lon = ceiling(max(obs_data$Longitude))
min_lon = floor(min(obs_data$Longitude))
geographic_extent = extent(x = c(min_lon, max_lon, min_lat, max_lat))

Download worldmap data and then plot. Lets add in some pie charts, adjust the radius and jitters as needed

world_map = world(resolution = 3,
                   path = "data/")
my_map = crop(x = world_map, y = geographic_extent)
plot(my_map, axes = TRUE, col = "grey95", xlim = c(min_lon - 1, max_lon + 1), ylim = c(min_lat - 1, max_lat + 1))
colors = c("red", "lightblue","#334989ff")
for (i in 1:nrow(obs_data)) {
  segments = c(obs_data$Aaa[i], obs_data$AafE[i],obs_data$AafW[i])
    floating.pie(
    xpos = obs_data$Longitude[i], 
    ypos = obs_data$Latitude[i], 
    x = segments, 
    radius = .5,  
    col = colors
  )
}

for (i in 1:nrow(obs_data)) {
  label_x = obs_data$Longitude[i] + runif(1, 0.4, 1)  # Jitter x further away
  label_y = obs_data$Latitude[i] + runif(1, 0.4, 1)    # Jitter y further away
  
  # Draw a line from the pie chart to the label
  segments(
    x0 = obs_data$Longitude[i], y0 = obs_data$Latitude[i],  # Start at pie chart
    x1 = label_x, y1 = label_y,  # End at label position
    col = "black"
  )
  # Add the label at the end of the line
  text(
    x = label_x, 
    y = label_y, 
    labels = obs_data$POP[i], 
    cex = 0.7,  # Adjust text size as needed
    col = "black"
  )
}
